    { "@type": "Question", "name": "What should a CLAUDE.md file look like?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A good CLAUDE.md file includes five sections: project overview (stack and purpose), file structure (where code lives), coding conventions (naming, formatting, patterns), testing setup (commands and frameworks), and guardrails (what Claude should never do). The exact content depends on your project type, but every config should cover all five areas." }},
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "How long should a CLAUDE.md file be?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Most effective CLAUDE.md files are between 80 and 200 lines. Under 50 lines usually means you are missing critical sections. Over 300 lines means Claude spends too many tokens reading your config instead of working on your code. Aim for specific, actionable rules rather than long descriptions." }},
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Does CLAUDE.md work with monorepos?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. Monorepos benefit the most from CLAUDE.md because they have the most complex file structures. You can use a root-level CLAUDE.md for shared conventions and additional CLAUDE.md files in each package for package-specific rules. Claude Code reads the closest CLAUDE.md to the file it is editing." }},
